:: Alexis {"position":"6700,500","size":"100,100"}
[You are in a relationship with Alexis, they know you are a werewolf]

"So.... where are we going exactly?" You ask, pushing a branch out of the way.

You've been walking through the forest for a while, Alexis is a few steps ahead, though they keep glancing back to check on you.
They stop, turning, a slight smile tugging at the corner of their mouth. 

"It's close."

A ray of sunlight slips through the canopy and catches the side of their hair, making their hazel eyes glow faintly in the light. They always seem more at ease out here. Especially when it's just the two of you. 

It's funny how things can change with the right person.

"How close?" You ask

They look at you, clearly amused. They always manage to resist your puppy eyes but you never fail to try each time nonetheless.

"Close enough."

Grandma was very talkative, and Lou is as well. You faintly wonder if it was a defense mechanism you learned. To surround yourself with chatty folks so you don't hear how overwhelming silence is. How alone it can make you feel.

It is one of the thing that always surprised you with Alexis. How comfortable silence could be.

When your grandma died, silence was all that you could hear and it was overwhelming. Werewolves are not meant to be alone. Not like you were. As much as you like your quiet alone time, loneliness can kill your kind. The suffocating silence was enough to drive you a little crazy with grief.
You can't help but wonder if the solitude is the reason you turned into a monster.
You grimace as you push the memory away.

You sniff the air and smell petrichor and wilderness. You think you smell the faint scent of a badger somewhere.

"We're here."

It is a small clearing, with a tiny lovely river going through it, some fallen logs have been assembled as a makeshift campfire, and you see a blanket, with a basket full of from what you can smell of food

A picnic. In the middle of the woods. 

They made this. Prepared all of it, for you. While you're still catching up to the gesture, all you manage is.

"Why?"

Alexis looked unbothered by the question. They only shrug in answer, "You were in pain." You also hear what's left unsaid; I wanted to do something //for you//.

Its true. The full moon was only a few days ago, and the days leading up to it had hit you harder than usual, body aching all over. And while you feel completely fine now, it is a very nice gesture to remember past pain.

You're not sure how long you stand there, just looking at it. Outside of your grandma, no one ever did anything like that for you. You start to wonder if maybe you've offended them but no, they simply wait for your answer, patient as ever. You get the feeling that if that made you uncomfortable they'd quietly pack it all away and never bring it up again.

That's one of the things you love most about Alexis. They give you room. Space to feel whatever you're feeling without rushing you. 

But you know them well enough now to see past the still face they wear. There's worry there, in the slight crease between their brows, the way their lips tighten ever so slightly into a straight line.

So you answer the best way you can with them, with physical touch. You hug them tight. As usual it takes a split second before Alexis hugs you tightly too. They're still learning how to be held like this, how to be loved out loud, but the gap closes a little more every time. It makes you smile against their shoulder. 

"Thank you."

"Of course" they press a kiss to your temple.

You sit together. Alexis unpacks the food. It’s nothing elaborate. Simple things, but it doesn't matter. Happiness, you're learning, doesn't need to be elaborate. It's something you feel more and more, just by being near them.

You sit there with your muscles sore but no longer aching, eating an apple Alexis peeled badly, clumsily, with obvious care.

And for once, you feel at peace.


