:: Camille {"position":"6575,550","size":"100,100"}
When Camille invited you to an underground fight you told yourself it was purely to analyse their fighting style. What was it that grandma always said? “Keep your friends close but your enemies closer”.

After all, how many opportunities do you get to see your greatest adversary up close without the fear of getting shot at. ?
Besides, it's interesting to see the king's hunter, fight without their arquebus.

Yes. You tell yourself, when Camille asked you to accompany them, you said yes purely for strategy purposes.

Gone are the heavy cloaks of the hunters, and the royal coat of the arquebusier du roi. Instead they stand shirtless with only white pants and hand wrappings. Sweat cling to their body and the soft candlelights of the club almost make their skin glow.
They look up and give you a small smile, a nod, before returning to stretch their arms.

You hear the bell ring, and the crowd roar beside you, as both opponents start to circle around each other. Camille is bouncing on their feet, their movement swift and fluid, yet there’s a certain tension in them, like an animal waiting to pounce.

When you saw their adversary, a guy twice their size, step into the circular pit, you thought this was going to be a massacre. After all, Camille is an excellent shot, and while they are good at horse riding and able to weave their way easily through the forest, you thought close-range would be their weakness. 

But no, Camille surprised you. 

Perhaps you underestimated them. It does make you wonder what their weakness could be.

You see the giant’s shoulder turn, weight dragging through his hips, before the punch comes, air almost stirring in its wake. His fist, the size of a sledgehammer, aimed at Camille’s head. They easily duck beneath it. 

By the time his arm reaches its full stretch, the hunter has already slipped through his guard. A jab lends into his stomach. Another snaps upward brushing the giant’s cheekbone. A third kisses his mouth before he can close his guard. 

Short swift blows, nothing strong enough to end the fight, but enough to make the giant’s balance waver. He staggers back, eyes wide for a split second. 

Camille grins.

Suddenly the size of him seems to matter far less.

The fight club is buzzing with tension, you can smell sweat, blood and alcohol as if they were soaked in the walls themselves. They probably are.
Eager eyes stay glued to the fighters. People yelling encouragement to the one they betted on and groaning when they get punched.
The smell, the noises, the crowd could easily overwhelm you. It has been too long since your senses were bombarded and yet your own eyes only see Camille. You no longer hear people or smell the place, it's like your entire body is in tune with them and only them.

The big man lunges forward, driving his massive hand into the hunter’s shoulder with a thunderous smack. The crowd gasps, as the force rattles Camille’s arm and rocks them back on their feet.
The giant presses the attack, swinging a wide hook towards Camille’s ribs. They pivot, letting it graze past, and counters with a quick elbow to the side of his torso. Another heavy punch drives toward Camille’s head, but they lean back just in time.
The giant stumbles slightly, before adjusting his footing, and driving a hard shoulder into Camille’s chest. The hunter shifts their weight, absorbing the hit with a grunt. 
The giant snarls and spit on the ground as the hunter circles, testing his guard, reading their balance.
Spotting a slight shift in his stance, Camille steps closer, planting a foot against the inside of his thigh. Using it as a ledge, the hunter drives a knee into his gut. The blow steals the air from him, forcing him back a step.
The giant is visibly tired now, their guard no longer holds. You see an opening, a slack on their left side, a subtle dip of the shoulder and from the way Camille circles them like a shark, you know they must see it too
Then, just for a heartbeat, they glance up.
And wink at you.
You feel butterflies in your stomach until you feel it drop; the giant sees that they’re distracted and takes the opportunity to uppercut them before they can block or dodge. The Colossus doesn't even give the hunter a chance to recover as they, twice, land powerful blows across their face. You watch Camille stagger before they collapse on the ground.

You ignore the crowd, feeling your heart squeeze in a painful way, as you rush to their side. They’re spitting blood on the ground, but they’re alive. Although they look smaller now, with blood trickling from their mouth, split brow and noses. No longer the powerful, in control hunter, you came to know.

You gently take care of them, wiping the blood away from their face. They purposely avoid your gaze though, even if they sit tall, they look ashamed. 

“I’ve known you more focused”

There is no judgement in your voice, but you see them flinch nonetheless as you dab the cloth against the arch of their brow. 

“I know.” There’s something vulnerable in their eyes before they sigh and square their shoulders. Their gaze flickers to your eyes and lower before moving away.  

“I was distracted. I could assure you that it wouldn’t  happen again but I’m afraid I would be lying.”

“You were distracted? By what?” by whom? You stop yourself from asking.

You halt your movement, but your hand doesn't get away from their face. They slowly wrap their hand around your wrist, movement slow enough that you can back away at any time. You don’t feel the need to.

“I think you already know.”

Their eyes look so pretty in this light, deep soulful eyes so dark you could drown in it but oh, so warm. They smile, enough that you see a single dimple on their face, sitting taller as if they hadn’t lost in front of you. As if their face doesn’t look like they took a beating.

“Perhaps, with you beside me, I find I scarcely mind losing at all”


