''Spending Style:'' <<if $spendingStyle == "rat">><<if $personality == "quiet">>Money has never come easily, and you've never forgotten that. $grandma taught you to hold on to what you have. You do. Quietly, carefully, without fuss.<<elseif $personality == "angry">>Money is hard to come by and easy to lose. You know that better than most. So no, you don't throw it around. $grandma raised no fool.	<<elseif $personality == "kind">>You wish you could give more. But $grandma taught you early, hold onto what you have, because there will be days when you'll need it. You try to remember that, even when it's hard.<<elseif $personality == "funny">>Are you stingy? You prefer the term "financially cautious." $grandma called it survival. tomato, tomato.<<else>>Money has never come easily, and you've never forgotten that. $grandma taught you early — hold onto what you have, because there will be days when you'll need it.<</if>><<elseif $spendingStyle == "generous">><<if $personality == "quiet">>You give without making a show of it. $grandma used to say your father was a generous man. You don't know if that's true. But it seems to have found its way to you, quietly.	<<elseif $personality == "angry">>What is the point of having things if you can't use them? You give. It's not a big deal. Don't make it one.<<elseif $personality == "kind">>You've never been able to hold onto money for long, not that you've tried very hard. $grandma used to say your father was a generous man. It seems that found its way to you too. What is the point of having things, if not to share them?<<elseif $personality == "funny">>You are, as $grandma would say, "aggressively bad with money." In your defence, someone had to inherit your father's generosity. Apparently that someone was you. You're choosing to see it as a gift.
