:: EndPrologue [Intro] {"position":"700,450","size":"100,100"}
After that the king has no desire to touch the thing further. With a single curt nod, his servant, the one who had accompanied him to witness Mx. Antoine's kill, steps forward and lifts one of the beast's lips, revealing a row of teeth. Large. Uncommonly sharp.

The king says nothing.  He will not say it aloud, but he is impressed and more than that, he is pleased. His officer. His porte-arquebusier. His kill, in every way that matters. Camille Antoine had merely been the one holding the arquebus.

He finds himself wondering, briefly, whether the creature had been more fearsome before it met its end. Whether the thing that had killed a hundred people looked less like this, like something defeated and decomposing, and more like something worthy of the legend his subjects had built around it. Worthy of //him,// perhaps.

He supposes he'll never know. And frankly, it doesn't matter.

His examination is finished. With barely another glance at the beast, the king turns and walks away.

The journalists will be unsufferable about this, of course. They always are. Pathetic little men with their ink-stained fingers, tripping over themselves to be the first to declare the Beast dead as though they had anything to do with it.  As though any of them had done anything beyond selling fear and gossip to anyone willing to pay for it.

The Beast of Gévaudan is dead. Slain on //his// order, by //his// hunter. //His// trophy.

//Good riddance.//

