:: Hyacinthe {"position":"6575,300","size":"100,100"}
[You are not “quite” in a relationship with Hyacinthe, but there is heavy attraction on both side]

"I believe I must decline. There is a ball happening tonight and I shall do my best to avoid it."

"A.... a ball?" You study Hyacinthe and you can't quite discern whether they're lying or not. "Aren't those suppose to be fun?"

"I found them exceptionally boring, if I have to be honest."

"Really?" You can't quite keep the disappointment out of your voice.

Your grandma always loved dancing. There's fond moments you remember, where you would dance with her and spin her around just to see her smile and hear her laugh. You'd always meant to take her to a real one someday. Sadly it never happened.
 It made you curious about what a real ball would be though. To hear musicians and dance without a care in the world.

You take a look at Hyacinthe and they're lovely like this. Slightly disheveled. Hair tousled by the wind. With the sunlight gently caressing their face. If you're honest with yourself, you'd been looking forward to dancing with them too.

You won't admit that to their face. Not yet.

They must feel your gaze because they turn to look at you curiously, their smile seems to lose an edge, not quite as sharp.

“People always wanted to dance with me to get something out of me. It was never simply fun. It was" they pause searching for the proper word. "Dreadful?"

Ah. That makes sense. You're not sure why you didn't think of that before. Of course a bard would know exactly what that's like, having every noble wanting a song, a favour, a little piece of attention. That makes you feel a bit foolish and inconsiderate.

"My apologies" you say "For a second it seemed I lived in a world where balls would just be...Dancing and not nobles judging each other."

You hear them laugh all too wrong "Oh, but judging is my favorite part though" 

And there it is. The mask is back, and in full force, they're all toothy grin and jests.

"You don't say" You can't help but feel a pang of disappointment at seeing the vulnerability disappear so quickly.

"You should see some of the clothes the nobles wear. It's such a sight. Or the way they speak about the most dull subject, my lord." They laugh seemingly lost in memory. "One time I had a lord talk to me for more than three dances about acorns. Acorns. It was unbearable. "
"Surely they don't ask the bard to dance ?"
Something flickers across their face but it’s and gone before you can read it. "You'd be surprised what people ask of me."
They look in the distance. In the direction of,  what you know to be,  the nearest manor. 

"Shall we go to a ball then?"

"I— excuse me?"

They get close to you, so close you can feel their breath on the shell of your ear as they whisper in your ear.

"Let us go to the ball, you and I."

You feel yourself heat up at the proximity, your heart already thumbing loudly in your chest. You turn to face them, and the smug, knowing curve of their mouth tells you they're fully aware of what they just did. 

"To judges other people?” you manage, attempting a joke. “Please, I don’t need a fancy ball to do that" 

You expect them to joke back but they look— they look sincere. They look at you softly, adoringly. In a way that makes your chest go warm.

This feels almost too good to be true. You need to look away, to break away from them before they do. 

"I thought balls were boring" you say instead, frowning, waiting for the other shoe to drop. You know by now this dance that you both do, one step forward two steps back.

"They are, but I've never tried them with you.” A pause. "Perhaps they'll be more fun than I remember."

You look up to meet their eyes because, surely, they're making fun of you. You're fully frowning now and you watch, with great satisfaction, as they seem to lose their cool under the weight of your gaze. They huff, look away, and grimace. 

They're embarrassed. 

How precious.

"I want to dance with you" they admit so softly you almost believe you imagined it.

"Alright." You relent, taking a little pity on them. "Only if you're sure you can get us in." 

"I can manage that much," they say, a little too easily. "I am sure. About the dancing, that is." 

It's strange, but you think you're starting to understand how their mind works. You ask for them to stay, they flee. You give them an easy exit and they stay. You wonder if your commitment to one another will ever not feel like a shackle to them.

You smile despite the thought, and the small ache it leaves behind. They beam back, and grab your hand leading the way. You half expect them to let go once they know you're following.
They don't. Their fingers lace through yours instead.
 "I heard the count has excellent company tonight"

You laugh. That took you by surprise.

"Oh, do they now?" 

They smile then, eyes filled with mirth and they look relaxed and you hope — you wish that you will see this expression more often.


