:: Prologue [Intro] {"position":"450,450","size":"100,100"}
<div class="typed-text"><<typed120>>!PROLOGUE<</typed120>></div>
<div class="chapter-name">Of Wolves and Kings</div>
<div class="typed-text"><<typed60>>\''September 1766, Palace of Versailles''<</typed60>></div>
After nearly two years of entertainment, the king finds himself almost mournful to hear the beast has been slain.

	He understands, of course, the political convenience of it. After the war, his subjects had been restless, that particular twitchy energy of people with too much grief and not enough to direct it toward. A common enemy always helped with that.  There had been scandals too, naturally, but scandals are commonplace. 
    A murderous, unnameable creature stalking the hills of Gévaudan and defying every attempt to bring it down, that, had been something else entirely. 
    That had been //interesting.// 
    He'll admit, in the privacy of his own thoughts, that the hunt had been the most diverting thing to happen to him in years. He had almost considered joining the effort himself.
    
    Almost. 

	 He's glad he didn't, as he looks at the thing now. It's just a wolf. A large one, certainly, his servant had told him it weighed eighty-four kilograms, which he supposes is impressive for a wolf, but a wolf nonetheless. Two years. Two years of deaths and hunts and prayers and pamphlets, and it was //just// a wolf.

	He almost wants to laugh. A wolf. His subjects had conjured demons and werewolves and God knows what else from a large wolf with an appetite. Peasants will make a legend out of anything, he supposes. Give them something they don't understand and they'll dress it in fangs and folklore before the week is out. He can't entirely blame them. It is, after all, commoner’s nature to fear what one cannot explain.

	What he can blame, and what he has not forgotten, is the quiet murmuring from certain nobles— the wretches! — who had the audacity to suggest, in their delicate roundabout way, that the crown bore some responsibility for the deaths. That, perhaps, the king had not acted swiftly enough. That, perhaps, more could have been done. As if they had done anything beyond writing letters and spewing nonsense from the safety of their estates.

	Still. It had taken his own porte-arquebusier to finally put it down, which is something. Let them chew on that. 

	The king scrunches his noses in disgust as he inspects the beast.

//What is the color of your fur and your hair, Wolfkin?//
