:: Tavern1 {"position":"5075,425","size":"100,100"}
Perhaps it is because you worked, or perhaps it is because you've had a rough night, but a huge part of you needs to see Lou. Before you even realize, your feet are heading to the Inn.

The inn, La Lune Rousse, is the only thing that makes Tierce-Lieux remotely interesting. It stands at the middle of the village, beside the little footbridge, though "village" is generous and "middle" generous still. Tierce-Lieux is hardly more than a road: a single track that follows the river down through the gorge, wedged between two moutains, too steep, where nothing can be sown. The mountains lean in close enough that the sun arrives late and leaves early, and the days run short even in summer.

No one comes to Tierce-Lieux. They come through it. The track is the only easy passage between the high pastures above and the Allier below, so they pass, climbing to the summer grazing, or dropping down toward the Velay. Muleteers, pedlars, the drovers twice a year with their flocks, and now and then a man leading mules packed with goods — he'd sooner no one counted — slipping a cargo from one side of a border to the other. 
They water their beasts, take a bed and a hot meal off Lou, and are gone by morning. Even the one proper bridge, the big one, up at the head of the valley, pays its toll to the lord across the water, not the one who holds the village. The people of Tierce-Lieux cross it free, being of the place, and it's the strangers who feed the neighbour's purse. Which has suited no one for three generations, and surprised no one either.

The inn is the village's gathering place. Locals stop in for a drink once or twice a week, but most who pass through its door are strangers. Travelers glad of a fire and a roof before the next leg of the road.

Lou is the owner. Her aunt and uncle once ran the establishment, with Lou helping wherever she could. When they died, they left the inn to her. Since taking over, Lou has managed the place splendidly, turning it into the heart of the village.
And while she rarely has a moment to herself, you often head to the inn just to see her. Somehow, she always finds time for you, even on her busiest days.
Besides, being her closest friend comes with its advantages. She always gives you a good price...or free drinks.

When you enter, there's a few regulars there, you recognise Damien, Josephine and Louis who are all around a little less than eighteen summers and as usual, drinking in the corner. There's old Charles, who after taking care of the fields, goes for one drink before heading home to his husband. You see Pierre drinking with Charles, he also works the field, but contrary to Charles, he stays until the inn closes. You and Lou often had to carry him home because he was piss drunk.

Your eyes find Lou before anything else. She's not cooking yet, it’s too early for that, but she's moving through the room, taking orders, setting down drinks, exchanging a word here and there. 
She looks incredibly put together for this hour, her curly ginger hair is wrestled in a tight bun though a few rogue curls are escaping from it. 

When she spots you across the room her face splits into a huge grin, almost dazzling you. You’ve always wondered how one person ended up with so much joy anyway. 
However her smiles dim when she clocks the state of you. She's always been too observant for your liking. Fortunately or unfortunately, depending on the day.

You head straight to “your” table. It doesn't really belong to you, but you claimed it in a silent agreement. It's in the corner with your back against the wall, it allows you to spot everyone who comes in. Besides, it's a bit secluded so you quite enjoy that.

After serving Charles and Pierre, she heads straight to your table.

“What's wrong?”  The blunt tone makes you wince. No preamble. No easing into it. How very much like her.

[[Grunt noncommittaly|tavern2quiet][$quiet += 1]]
[[For some reason this question makes you angry.|tavern2angry][$angry += 1]]
[[Be Honest.|tavern2kind][$kind += 1]]
[[Banter back.|tavern2funny][$funny += 1]]
<<set $honest = 0>>


:: Welcome {"position":"125,750","size":"100,100"}
<span class="typed-text"><<typed>>Welcome to the Land of the Beast, Wolfkin.<</typed>></span>
	For nearly three years, a mysterious creature has terrorised the region of Gévaudan. Described by survivors as wolf-like and relentless, it kills indiscriminately, taking men, women and children alike, leaving behind only what the strongest could stomach. Many have taken up arms, from simple farmers and hunters to soldiers and even nobles hungry for glory. None have succeeded.
    
    To this day the mystery remains. Is it a wolf? A hyena? A werewolf? A wizard or even just a human murderer? Somewhere between folklore and nightmare, between cautionary tale and genuine terror, the Beast of Gévaudan still eludes all.
	Only one person knows the truth.
    
	//You.//
    
	Why?
    
	''Because you are the Beast of Gévaudan.''
    

''DISCLAIMER:''
	//While this story is based and inspired by France in the XVIII, you might notice there are some drastic changes. 
    
    France in 1760 (and even still to this day) is inseparable from its injustices. The Ancien Régime, the Tiers État, the Church's grip on people and their daily life;  they are the bones of this world. Religion and social class will be present and felt throughout this story.
    But I made a choice about the others. Misogyny, homophobia, racism, transphobia… These are equally real, equally woven into history, and I am not putting my head in the sand about that. 
    In this world, the fights were fought a century or so earlier. The changes were hard-won, and they left marks, you'll find the echoes in how characters speak around certain things, in the way some wounds haven't fully closed. But I cannot bring myself to write a story where those injustices are not only there but expected and amplified at every corner. That's not a world I want to spend time in because if I wanted that, I'd just step outside.

    This is not a perfectly historical story. It was never going to be one. (It has werewolves for fuck's sake!) But I'll try to make it an honest one, within the world I have chosen to build.//

''NOTE: Version 1.06''

Keep in mind this is a work in progress, I will add content warning later on :)
Thank you for reading it anyway. <3


Your character will have a disability, usually you would chose among the fellow three, but I havent written them yet so! I apologise for that:

	''Colorblind.'' The most common disability among werewolves. Red and Greens are difficult to distinguish, while you see predominantly in shades of Blue and Yellow. You've learned to work around it. Mostly.
	''Hard of Hearing.'' (under construction - sorry!)
	''Selective Mutism'' (under construction - sorry!)
    
