:: WoodCalm {"position":"1075,575","size":"100,100"}
<<set $stress +=  3>>
At this point, waking up bloodied and naked in the middle of the forest of Brameloup is your new normal. Funny, what becomes ordinary. The situation is odd, but you're not panicking. 

Not anymore. 

You've been tracking your habits carefully over these past months, making mental notes of what you can remember, what you find, where you wake. And the wolf doesn't seem reckless. It hunts. It eats. It stays in the forest. It doesn't stray toward the village, doesn't take unnecessary risks, doesn't leave a trail that anyone could easily follow. 

It's almost disciplined, in its own way. You're not sure whether that's reassuring or unsettling. 
Probably just ate a rabbit last night. Maybe a deer if you were particularly hungry.


[[At least for now.|wood2]]


:: WoodPanic {"position":"1075,450","size":"100,100"}
<<set $stress =  0>>
No matter how many times it happens this never stops being terrifying. Losing control,  the memory gaps. Losing control of yourself so completely that you wake up hours later with blood on your hands and no memory of how it got there. Not knowing what you did. What you killed. Whether it was just a rabbit or something worse, something that matters to someone, and you will never know because you weren't there, not really, just the wolf wearing your body like a coat.

It scares you. Deeply, in a way that hasn't dulled, no matter how many times you've lived through it.

How long can this go on before someone notices? Before someone takes a shortcut through the forest of Brameloup and finds you like this? 

	//Oh gods, you're full on panicking now aren't you?// 

[[Get a hold on yourself.|wood2]]


:: WoodRepressed {"position":"1075,325","size":"100,100"}
<<set $stress +=  1>>
Okay. Breathe. 

You inhale slowly. Exhale slower. Again. Your heart is hammering but you give it time, eyes closed, focusing on nothing but the air moving in and out of your lungs. 

In. Out. 

Gradually you feel your senses expand, the way they always do when you stop fighting them and simply let them be. You focus on your hearing, letting it stretch outward through the trees.

 The forest of Brameloup is loud, but not in an unpleasant way. A herd of deer moving somewhere deeper in, hooves soft against the earth. A small bird fussing over its nest nearby. The rustle of ants working through the undergrowth somewhere close by. The soft wind through the canopy.

But no footsteps. No voices. No humans. 

You feel yourself relax, muscle by muscle, the panic loosening its grip one breath at a time. 

[[That's a good sign.|wood2]]


:: bath1 {"position":"1850,425","size":"100,100"}
The basin had been set on the washstand since the day before. You always come back the same way. Dirty. Muddy. Bloody. Better to be prepared than to face it half-asleep.

Your grandmother's mirror sits propped beside the basin, small enough to fit in a palm, the handle worn smooth from years of her hands before yours. It's one of the only things you have left of her.
Next to the mirror is a cake of $soap, wrapped in linen. Then small bottles; the $shampoo, the $perfume, the $skincare. <<if $origin == "marseillais">>Things you brought with you when you left home.<<else>> Things you brought from far away lands. <</if>> Things that still smell like somewhere else. Like someone else.

	You pick up the mirror out of habit, and immediately wish you hadn't.
You look terrible. Worse than usual, even by your own forgiving standards. Your <<cycle "$texture" autoselect>>
	<<option "straight">>
	<<option "wavy">>
	<<option "curly">>
    <<option "coily">>
<</cycle>> hair is a disaster. Matted and tangled with something dark and crusted that you'd rather not identify.  Your <<cycle "$facialHair" autoselect>> 
	<<option "bare jaw" "none">>
	<<option "freshly shaven jaw" "clean shaven">>
	<<option "stubbled jaw" "stubble">>
	<<option "beard" "beard">>
	<<option "goatee" "goatee">>
	<<option "moustache" "moustache">>
	<<option "sideburns" "sideburns">>
	<<option "mutton chops" "mutton chops">>
	<<option "chin strip" "chin strip">>
	<<option "chin strap" "chin strap">>
<</cycle>> is faring no better, flecked with the same. The old scar along your <<cycle "$scar" autoselect>>
	<<option "cheek">>
	<<option "brow">>
	<<option "jaw">>
	<<option "neck">>
<</cycle>> stands out paler than usual against the grime. There's dried blood at the corner of your mouth. You touch it with one finger, almost absently.

For someone who likes to be clean, coming back each month this way hurts you.

	<<if $warmbath == "true">>Steam clings faintly to the earthenware, the water within warmed just enough to take the bite out of the morning chill.<<else>>The water is cold. Bracingly, unpleasantly cold. You grit your teeth.<</if>>

	A cake of $soap rests beside it, wrapped in linen.

You undress and dip the cloth into the basin, wringing it out before drawing it across your neck and shoulders, then your arms. And as your hands move you let your mind drift back to the night before.

You remember the dull pain behind your eyes. The sharp one at the base of your skull, as if the wolf was pushing to be let out. You remember the utter relief of running, right after the transformation, that first breath of night air, the soft ground underneath your paws.

	After that, it fragments.

	//What do you remember?// 

	Pain, fear, //hunger//. 
	So much hunger.

<<if $warmbath == "false">>	The cold makes you hiss through your teeth but you don't stop.
<<else>>The $smell scent rises faintly with the steam, softened by the trace of $perfume in the water. You barely notice it.<</if>>

	The water turns grim, brownish red.

	A rifle shot. The echo of whimpers. The sound of flesh being torn apart. Cries of pups.

	//Make it Stop.//

	Blood. A deep rooter pain. Hunger. Anger. And underneath it all, fear. Father is gone. Mother still doesn't move. Home isn't home anymore. Even then it felt wrong. 

	Rotten.

[[ENOUGH.|bath2]]




:: bath2 {"position":"1975,425","size":"100,100"}
You can't breathe, it feels like you're drowning. Drowning in memories and sorrow and pain and—

You need to breathe.

//Breathe//

It takes a while to come back to yourself. You don't know how long you stand there, hands gripping the basin so hard your knuckles ache.

You're not sure what opened that door. Memories you hadn't touched in decades, buried deep enough you'd almost convinced yourself they were gone. But something reached in and pulled them out loose, and now you can't quite get it shut again. 
It's frustrating, because it was around the same time the wolf first began to manifest. As if grief and the curse had always been tangled up in each other. Maybe that's why you couldn't transform while that door stayed closed.

You wish it had opened while your grandmother was still here. She would know what to do. But you suspect her death is what pulled it open in the first place.

Those memories don't visit gently. They never do. They leave you with a ragged unsteady breath and tears caught at the corners of your eyes.

<<if $stress >= 4>>You breathe. In and out, slow and steady, until the edges soften. Until you're just standing in your house again. Until you feel like you again.<<elseif $stress >= 2>>You let yourself cry. Just for a moment. Just until it passes.<<else>>You laugh. And keep laughing, until you can't breathe again, until it sounds wrong even to your own ears. Because what else is there to do? This whole situation is so utterly, completely //absurd//. <</if>>

You're still dirty, you need to finish.

You work through the rest of it then you straighten up. The water in the basin has gone dark, brownish red. You look into it anyway, and your reflection looks back. Distorted. Monstrous in the low light.

You notice your hair.

Right.  Should take care of that too.

