:: bath3 {"position":"2100,425","size":"100,100"}
<<if $length == "bald" || $length == "buzzcut">>
It's a short affair. You pour water over your head and let it run, fingers moving in small circles across your scalp, lifting dust, mud and whatever else was stuck in there. You take your time with the massage. It soothes you more than you'd like to admit.<br><br>You rinse then, you uncork a little bit of $shampoo and get a knob on your finger as you lightly apply it across your head. You don't really need it but you like the smell, it reminds you of easier times.
<<elseif $length == "short above your ears">>
You tip your head forward and use a smaller jug to pour water over the crown, making sure everything is thoroughly wet. Water trickles down your forehead and temples, catching in the basin below.<br><br>Fingers move in small circles across your scalp, lifting dust and mud and whatever else was stuck in there. You take your time with the massage. It soothes you more than you'd like to admit.<br><br>You rinse. Then you uncork a little bit of $shampoo and get a knob on your finger as you lightly apply it on your hair, <<if $texture == "straight">>styling it as you go.<<elseif $texture == "wavy">>detangling with your fingers as you go. You scrunch the waves loosely with your palms, not forcing anything, just encouraging them back into shape.<<elseif $texture == "curly">>detangling with your fingers as you go. You rinse again, thorough this time, before applying a little more sparingly, sealing it in. The curls find their shape on their own, defined by your hands rather than forced into anything.<<elseif $texture == "coily">>patiently, section by section, detangling then separating curls one at a time. Stretching each curl gently between your fingers. The coils hold their shape.<</if>>
<<elseif $length == "braided close to your scalp">>
You tip your head forward and use a smaller jug to pour water over the crown, making sure everything is thoroughly wet. Water trickles down your forehead and temples, catching in the basin below.<br><br>Fingers move in small circles across your scalp, lifting dust and mud and whatever else was stuck in there. You take your time with the massage. It soothes you more than you'd like to admit.<br><br>You rinse. Then you uncork the bottle of $shampoo <<if $texture == "straight">>and work it through from root to tip. You rinse again, thoroughly this time, then dry the excess with the linen towel, pale and worn smooth by years of use, pressing rather than rubbing.<<elseif $texture == "wavy">>smoothing it through from root to tip, detangling with your fingers as you go. You rinse again, thorough this time, before blotting the excess with the linen towel, pale and worn smooth by years of use, leaving your hair damp rather than wet.<<elseif $texture == "curly">>applying it in sections, detangling with your fingers as you go, then rinsing again. Your curls will find their shape on their own, better to work with them now while everything is still damp.<<elseif $texture == "coily">>applying it patiently, section by section, detangling, then separating each coil gently between your fingers. The coils hold their shape. By the time you're done your hair is still damp but considerably more manageable, ready to be worked.<</if>><br><br>While everything is still damp you go through it in sections, rebraiding as you go, letting the hair settle neatly into place as it dries. Then you take a little more of the $product and tap it in where it needs it, gently, protecting and sealing each braid.
<<elseif $length == "short locs" || $length == "long locs">>
You tip your head forward and use a smaller jug to pour water over your locs, taking your time to make sure they're thoroughly soaked through, not just the surface, but down to the scalp.<br><br>Fingers move in small circles across your scalp first, lifting dust and mud and whatever else made its way in there overnight. You take your time with the massage. It soothes you more than you'd like to admit.<br><br>You work the $shampoo in next, starting at the scalp and easing it down through the length of each loc, patient and unhurried. There's no rushing this part. You rinse until the water runs clean, which takes longer than you'd like, but you've learned not to cut corners here.<br><br>Drying takes its own kind of patience. You press the linen towel carefully through, section by section, drawing the water out without disturbing the shape, no rubbing, no twisting, just steady pressure until the worst of it is gone.<br><br>Where there's new growth near the scalp you palm roll, slow and deliberate, retwisting where it needs it. Your hands know this by now, even half-asleep.<br><br>Last, you work in a little of the mixture, smoothing it along each loc to seal everything in.
<<else>>
You lean forward and let your hair fall loose. You use a smaller jug to pour water over the crown, making sure everything is thoroughly wet. Water trickles down your forehead and temples, catching in the basin below.<br><br>You move your fingers in small circles across your scalp first, lifting dust and mud and whatever else was stuck in there, careful not to scrape. You take your time with it. It soothes you more than you'd like to admit.<br><br>You rinse.<br><br><<if $texture == "straight">>You work the soap through from root to tip, then rinse. You dry the excess with a linen towel, pale and worn smooth by years of use. Then you work through any tangles with your fingers while the hair is still damp. Then you get a small amount of $shampoo in your palms, before applying sparingly to the ends, leaving your hair feeling like silk.<<elseif $texture == "wavy">>You apply the $shampoo, smoothing it through from root to tip, detangling with your fingers as you go. You rinse again, thorough this time, before drying the excess with a linen towel, pale and worn smooth by years of use, dabbing it lightly leaving your hair damp. Then you get a small amount of $shampoo in your palms, applying just a little more sparingly to the ends, sealing it in. You scrunch the waves loosely with your palms, not forcing anything, just encouraging them back into shape.<<elseif $texture == "curly">>You apply the $shampoo in sections, detangling with your fingers as you go, then you rinse again. You get a small amount of the mixture in your palms this time, before applying a little more sparingly, crunching the curls, sealing them in. They find their shape on their own, defined by your hands rather than forced into anything. It's still wet, but you'll leave it to dry naturally.<<elseif $texture == "coily">>You apply the $shampoo patiently, section by section, detangling then separating curls one at a time. Stretching each curl gently between your fingers. The coils hold their shape. By the time you're done, your hair is still wet but considerably less so, you'll leave it to dry naturally.<</if>><</if>><br><br>The $smell scent lingers faintly in the air.<br><br>[[All done, then.|bath3.5]]


:: bath3.5 {"position":"2225,425","size":"100,100"}
You grimace. Your skin feels tight and dry after cleaning. You uncork the bottle of $skincare and work it in slowly, taking stock of your body as you go; a bruise along the ribs you don't remember getting, another at the hip, a small cut on your calf. You make a note of each one, cataloguing.

A small vial of $perfume next. Just a little bit applied along the nape of your neck and the inside of your wrists. You feel, if not human, then at least something close to it.
