:: bath4 {"position":"2350,425","size":"100,100"}
You've been at this for at least an hour. Maybe two. Maybe three even. And yet even physically clean you still feel it, that particular filthiness that soaked your soul where soap can't quite reach. You pick at your nails, cleaning them as best as you can. 

    You put on clothes then you go looking for your grandmother's mirror. You need to make sure you don't look like you woke up naked in the middle of a forest this morning.

//Do you look as awful as you feel?//

Almost.

You look tired. Your <<cycle "$eyes" autoselect>>
	<<option "grey">>
	<<option "brown">>
	<<option "black">>
    <<option "green">>
    <<option "blue">>
    <<option "hazel">>
<</cycle>> eyes are haunted by the look of someone who has seen something they can't quite name. Dark rings sit beneath them, deep enough that no amount of sleep would fully explain them away.<<if $length != "bald">> But your $fur $texture hair looks clean and soft, which counts for something. <<endif>>
Your <<cycle "$undertone" autoselect>>
	<<option "warm">>
	<<option "neutral">>
	<<option "cool">>
<</cycle>> <<cycle "$skin" autoselect>>
	<<option "ivory">>
	<<option "rosy">>
	<<option "tan">>
    <<option "brown">>
    <<option "black">>
    <<option "ebony">>
<</cycle>> skin, looks dull, washed out. But no smell of blood anymore. No traces of mud either. You look like someone who slept badly and is suffering for it.

There's still a wildness in your eyes that you can't quite smooth away. Anyone who knows you would clock it immediately, but that list is short anyway. To everyone else you look fine.

	Fine is exactly what you need.

	//Can't have people finding you cagey if you just ate their pets.//

You're wearing:
[[Short tunic and some pants|bath5][$clothes to "masculine"]]
[[A robe|bath5][$clothes to "feminine"]]


:: bath5 {"position":"2475,425","size":"100,100"}
The clothes are yours, pulled from your own wardrobe, but it's been long enough since you had money to spend on anything you actually liked that the distinction barely matters. They're clean. They fit. They're considerably better than what you woke up in, which is to say, nothing, and infinitely better than those itchy things you had to wear on the way home.

It could be worse.

Someday, you think, smoothing over your sleeve. When you have more coin. When you have more control. You'll buy things that actually feel like you.

Someday.

[[Next|Name]]


:: blacksmith [blacksmith] {"position":"3300,500","size":"100,100"}
There is not much you remember about your parents. Most of it you were just a cub and the rest you tried to erase. But you've never quite been able to shake the memory of visiting your mother's forge. The heat would strike you the moment you got close, the smell of hot iron and coal smoke settling into your clothes and hair. It was overwhelming and yet you remember feeling safe.
 
You remember how happy she looked when she was crafting things, your mother. Focused. Alive. So different from the last memories you have of her. 

Maybe that's why you picked it up. To be closer to her.

$grandma always said it's important to be well rounded in your knowledge, so you picked up a bit of everything. Edge tool making, locksmithing, tinsmith, sheet metal work and even a little bit of gunsmithing.
You're far from being a prodigy but you're good enough for the locals and that's good enough for you. For now at least.

When you first arrived in Tierce-Lieux you built your own forge. It's far from perfect but it's yours. You never thought you'd have one. Growing up it had always been someone else's forge, someone else's tools, someone else's fire. Standing in front of your own for the first time, even a crooked one, felt like something you didn't quite have a word for. 

You didn't expect to become quite so popular but it seemed the place was in dire need of a blacksmith.

Is that the job that you have ?

[[Yes.|blacksmith1]]
[[No.|job2]]




:: blacksmith1 [blacksmith] {"position":"3425,500","size":"100,100"}
<<set $job to "blacksmith">>
	Business has been quiet for a few days. Luckily for you, you were in pain and feeling a bit drowsy with the full moon coming up.
You take one last look at the mirror making sure you look at least presentable, and then go reach for the door.

	As you open, you see an older man, Augustin Boulet, skin tanned from work spend outside, auburn hair with a few hints of white hair, a full beard and and darke eyes hidden under a stern look with frowned bushy brows. He’s a shepherd, and he and his family are your closest neighbors. You often see their sheep in the field right next to your house, sometimes even in your garden. Not that you mind since they take care of the grass.

	As he sees you he straightens up a little. 

[[He's not alone thought.|blacksmith2.5]]




:: blacksmith11 [blacksmith] {"position":"4425,500","size":"100,100"}
Augustin hands you the key as you step up. The barn door is sagged on its hinge and the lock hungs loose.

You grab the lock and turn it over in your hands. The iron case is thick, hammered square at the edges, the surface scaled from years of weather.
You try to slid the key in but it get stucks halfway through. 

"Probably rust and a tired spring" You think outloud.

Its not the most complex work to do, but still it should take the day. 
There's two possibility here: You could fix the existing lock. Not the best choice in terms of life span, but the one which will cost less for your customers. The other would be to make a brand new one. You know that whatever you chose, the Boulet will be able to pay you regardless. 

[[You can fix the existing lock.|fixingLock]]
[[You can make a brand new lock.|newLock]]




:: blacksmith12 [blacksmith] {"position":"4675,500","size":"100,100"}
The new lock is set into the thick wooden door with hand-forged screws. You give the key to Augustin and sees him test it. Once, twice and then tuck the key into his coat. 

“Let the wolves push on that!” He smiles at you.

You wipe your hands on your apron. <<if $newLock == "true">>
Well now, the lock should be able to outlast the both of you, if the hinges hold that is...
<<else>>If Augustin oils it from time to time, it should be able to last a few decades before it breaks again.
<<endif>>

"Well, thanks"

[[“Of course.”|JobFinal]]




:: blacksmith2.5 {"position":"3550,500","size":"100,100"}
	You see the eldest of the Boulet twins. Élise. She's no more than 15 winters. Tall, with the thick brows of her father, crooked nose of her mother but gentle smile that is all of her own. 
	Usually she's found helping out her mother, she made you a few tarts in the past few years. The first few one were a bit atrocious but she, thankfully, quickly got better. You're pretty sure she's been harboring some sort of hero crush on you. You cannot fathom why. Still, because of it she seems to have gotten a genuine interest in the culinary art. 
    
 	Lou is fond of her, so you suspect that soon enough she'll get a proper job at the inn.  
She's considered by the entire village as the eldest because of how responsible she is. Although you personally rarely see that side of her.
  
[[Next.|blacksmith4]]




:: blacksmith4 [blacksmith] {"position":"3675,500","size":"100,100"}
You look at them expectantly. Augustin shifts his weight from one foot to the other, not quite meeting your eyes.

“The lock on the barn broke yesterday. You mind taking a look at it?” He eyes you at the corner of his eyes, fidgety in the way he always is around people. 

You can help but cock your head asking a silent question. 

He sniffs, and wipes his palms against his already dirty pants. “Sorry, You look like you slept badly.”

He’s always been awkward. When you first arrived you thought it was suspicion, a stranger in a small village, people talk. But you've known him long enough now to understand it's simply how he is. Augustin Boulet prefers the company of his sheep to most humans. You can’t really blame him there.

"Are you okay ?" The youngling blurts out.

You catch her looking at you, with the particular directness children haven't yet learned to disguise. It's still odd to you, to be the center of someone else's attention like that. For so long it was just you and your grandma, small quiet world with no one looking too closely. 

You must look terrible. You know you must.

But then, you see her turning her head back at the road waiting for your answer. Whatever she saw, she's way too polite, too kind, to comment on it. 

You sigh. 

	//How long can you keep this up? //

[['"I'm fine.'"|blacksmith5]]




:: blacksmith5 [blacksmith] {"position":"3800,500","size":"100,100"}
“I’m fine” you snip, words sounding harsher than you meant.

Your reaction surprises her. You watch it cross her face — the confusion, then the blush, then the dawning realization that she's stumbled into something too personal. For a moment she looks like she'd very much like to disappear into the nearby forest.

Anne-Marie frowns at her.

//Damn it. //

It's not her fault. None of this is her fault. She's been nothing but kind to you, and here you are, bristling like a wounded animal at a child asking a simple question. You have secrets and no one to carry them with, but that's your burden, not hers.

You make an effort. It costs you, but you make it. You consciously unclench your jaw, letting the tension bleed out of your shoulders. You can do this. You can be a person for five minutes.

You exhale, and feel yourself soften.

That's when you notice she's been holding something behind her back.

"Whatcha got here?"

Her whole face changes. The embarrassment evaporates instantly, replaced by something luminous and proud, as she hoists a pie above her head with both hands like she's presenting a trophy.

"I baked you a pie!"

[["Really? What kind?"|blacksmith6]]




:: blacksmith6 {"position":"3925,500","size":"100,100"}
"Blueberry." You look down at it. Still warm, by the feel of it, the crust is golden and a little asymmetrical in the way of something made with great enthusiasm and developing skill.
You tuck the pie under your arm before she can offer to carry it inside for you or, worse, suggest you share it right now.

"Thank you, Elise. Really." You mean it, despite yourself.

You see her cheeks flush and suppress a sigh.

You know how it goes with kids. They pick an adult, decide that adult is somehow worthy of their admiration, and there's that. You still have no idea what you did to make her choose //you// of all people. At first you assumed it was novelty, the new face in a small village, but that was years ago and she hasn't grown out of it yet. You live in hope.

You wonder, not for the first time, what she'd think if she could see you as you really are. Half-naked at dawn, caked in mud and worse, crouched over something small and dead on the ground. 
//Still think I'm so impressive then?//

Still. It's not hurting anyone. And you'd rather not be the reason a kid's feelings get stepped on just because you're not comfortable being looked at like that.

You decide to redirect before she gets any more attached to this conversation.

[[”How's your mother?”|blacksmith7]]




:: blacksmith7 [blacksmith] {"position":"4050,500","size":"100,100"}
"Oh!" She seems surprised. "Mother is good, the little one got sick so she's taking care of her."

"Jeanne did not come home last night" Augustin Interject.

While Elise is well liked by everyone, Jeanne however is Augustin's favorite. Probably because like him, she's likely to follow in his footsteps and become a shepherd as well. 

"Jeanne? Please father, we all know she probably found some berries in the woods and is too busy eating them rather than actually working." She says, rolling her eyes.

"Enough." Augustin's voice is stern, leaving no room for arguments. Elise deflates.

"When did she leave ?" You ask, and you can see Elise thanking you silently for taking the attention off of her.

"Oh, well she went on a walk with our dog yesterday morning, but neither came back."

It is not unusual. Jeanne, while being a very sweet child, always had her head in the clouds. You often found her napping next to a tree, or simply taking care of the animals lost in time. She befriended a badger once, before it scratched her hand.

"Im sure she is fine, like your daughter said, she probably simply lost track of time"

He grumbles but doesn't say more. From the look of things, Augustin doesn't look convinced at all, but he's gracious enough to let it go.

