:: coldbath {"position":"1700,375","size":"100,100"}
<<set $stress += 1>><<set $warmbath to "false" >>
The day after a transformation is, at least, easier on the body than the days before. The aches are gone. The Moon is generous that way, whatever the curse breaks she puts back together by morning. Joints and muscles that screamed yesterday are silent and steady now.

You should be grateful for that. Probably.

It doesn't make the monthly ritual of it any less exhausting. The healing is real, but so is everything that preceded it. The bone-deep pain of the days before, the transformation itself, and then the morning after, when you come back to yourself piece by piece and have to figure out what you've done.

The body recovers. The rest takes longer.

The cold water will not help with that. You know this. Perhaps that's partly why you chose it. Something small and punishing, a way of marking the night for what it was. Or perhaps it's simply practical; the shock of it will wake you up faster than anything else could, after the night you've had. Maybe even make you remember what you did.

It doesn't matter the reason.

Still, first things first you need to be methodical and clean your house. Keep your hands busy. Keep moving.

You fold the clothes you'd shed in a hurry last night, before you take the broom. The dried mud had followed you with you this morning and is caked into the grain of the wood, you start weeping in long steady strokes. Sweeping helps. It keeps your mind from circling back

By the time the house looks like itself again, you've run out of reasons to delay.

The basin is waiting.

[[Now. You.|bath1]]


:: doctor [Doctor] {"position":"3300,350","size":"100,100"}
You always had a knack for helping people. And while for the longest time you did not have the gift of the transformation, your grandma taught you how to read the forest. Which plants heal, which harmed, which did both depending on how you used them.
Your most prized possession is an anatomy book you acquired before arriving in Tierce-Lieux. You've read it so many times by now that you barely need to open it anymore. Which is fortunate, because it's barely holding itself together. The spine gave out long ago under the weight of use, the pages dog-eared and covered in your own cramped notes in the margins.

Being a werewolf has its uses, in this line of work. The sick have a particular scent clinging to them. You often know something is wrong before the patient does. 

The spare room that you built in your house became your studies where you examined people when they came to you. 
When you first arrived in Tierce-lieux you were surprised by how welcoming everyone was, even more so when they learned that you could help heal them. Even neighbors from other villages came knocking at your door. 

$grandma always said it's important to be well rounded in your knowledge, so you picked up a bit of everything. Medicinal tonics, herbal remedies, poultice, and even surgery once. You're far from being a prodigy, but you're good enough, and good enough has kept people alive. For now at least.

And while you do consider yourself a physician you know that you technically don't have the proper title, as one is required to pass a fancy expensive exam in the Capital, and you've never cared about it that much.
You didn't expect to become quite so popular but it seemed the place was in dire need of a doctor.

Is that the job you have?

[[Yes.|doctor1]]
[[No.|job2]]




