:: fixingLock {"position":"4550,500","size":"100,100"}
Well then, back to the forge it is.

Once you're back to your workshop, you set the lock near the edge of the forge until the metal grows warm, not glowing orange though, just warm enough to drive out the damp.
The scent of heated iron and old oil rise into the air. With a small hammer you start to punch the side plate loose. You see the interior, fixed iron ribs that forces the key to follow its precise path.
The spring has cracked clean through.

From a strip of iron you start to create a new spring, thining it under steady blows.
Hammers strikes ring through the forge. Measured and Precised. In perfect Rythm.
//Clang clang clang//. 
You love the repetitive movement, there's something soothing to it. It always manages to calm you down. <<cycle "$whistle" autoselect>>
    <<option "You whistle while you work. ">>
    <<option "Beside the usual noise from the forge, you like working in silence.">>
<</cycle>>
You then quench it in the slack tub where steam bursts. 
When you take it out you start to test it and when you see it bent slightly then come back to its original shape you nod to yourself.

You start to fit the new spring and close the case. 

You fill the key just in case, decades of use worn it.

Then you test the lock.  the key goes through, then you hear a satifying click as you turn it.

By afternoon, You walk back to the Boulet's barn. Augustin is working with his sheep when he sees you he nods and joins you after a bit.

"There, good as new." you hand the lock back. "Should hold your sheep better than before. Oil it every once in a while"

[[Next.|blacksmith12]]
<<set $newLock to "false">>




