:: newLock {"position":"4550,650","size":"100,100"}
Well then, back to the forge it is.

You chose a bar of wrough iron from the rack along the wall, testing for flaws. That one should be perfect.

You bury the bar deep in the heart of the coals. You press the bellows and hear it sigh before it roars.
Sparks starts to climb the chimney like fireflies.
When the iron starts to glow that beautiful yellow-orange color that you love, you draw it out and lay it accross the anvil. 
The first blow is to flatten it, squaring it folding it till it forms the lock's case.
Hammers strikes ring through the forge. Measured and Precised. In perfect rythm.
//Clang clang clang.//
You love the repetitive movement, there's something soothing to it. It always manages to calm you down. <<cycle "$whistle" autoselect>>
	<<option "You whistle while you work. ">>
	<<option "Beside the usual noise from the forge, you like working in silence.">>
<</cycle>>

You bend the hot metal around a form block, shaping it into a shallow box. A second plate would close it later.
Next comes the bolt. You draw out a thick section, hammering one end into a rectangular tongue that will slide into the door frame. You leave the other end broad to receive the spring.
The wards, the hidden ribs inside that will only move for the proper key, are forged from slender strips, heated and riveted into place within the case. Each is set carefully. Too loose, and any crude key might turn it. Too tight, and even the right key would jam.

For the spring, you work a thin strip again and again, heating, hammering, quenching. You temper it to a dark blue at the edge of the fire, judging the color by eye alone. A brittle spring would snap; a soft one would fail to drive the bolt.

Only then do you begin working on the key.
From a narrow rod you forge the bow, a simple oval, then draw out the shaft. The bit you shape slowly, cutting away with file and chisel until its pattern matches the narrow path between the wards.

The lock case is closed with rivets, peened tight while still hot. You cool it, file the seams smooth, and fix it in the vise.

Then, you take the key and slid it into the lock.
Unfortunately the first turn does nothing. 
Huh. 

You remove the back plate, fil one ward thinner, and reassemble.

The second turns but gets stuck. 

Again you open it, adjust the spring tension, polish the bolt’s edges. 
On the third attempt, the key turns cleanly. You smiled faintly. Third time's the charm.

By afternoon, You walk back to the Boulet's barn. Augustin is working with his sheep when he sees you he nods and joins you after a bit.

[[Next.|blacksmith12]]
<<set $newLock to "true">>




