:: tavern10louf {"position":"6275,350","size":"100,100"}
 She stares into her drink and adds more quietly “I just don't want to be alone, you know?”
<<if $quiet > $funny and $quiet > $angry and $quiet > $kind>> <<set $personality to "quiet">><<elseif $funny > $quiet and $funny > $angry and $funny > $kind>><<set $personality to "funny">><<elseif $angry > $quiet and $angry > $funny and $angry > $kind>><<set $personality  to "angry">><<elseif $kind > $quiet and $kind > $funny and $kind > $angry>><<set $personality to "kind" >><</if>>
“What do you mean? You’re not alone. I’m here” You pause then add “but I know exactly what you mean.” 

You catch the glint in her eye a half-second too late. "Well." She tilts her head. "At least you’re right on that. I do have you, even if you're a little too $personality...." 

<<if $personality == "angry">>You feel your eyes narrow. "Excuse me?"

She gives you a look that says she absolutely does not excuse you.
You hold her gaze for a moment before something cracks and you laugh despite yourself.<<elseif $personality == "quiet">>You laugh quietly, just once, under your breath.

"See," she says, pointing at you, "you're proving my point. Even when you laugh you're quiet."

You laugh again, properly this time.<<elseif $personality == "funny">>"Oh no." You press a hand to your chest, sarcasm dripping from your voice. "I'm laughing far too much lately. I genuinely preferred when life was miserable and everything was awful."

She stares at you. "See, you're proving my point."

That, makes you laugh.<<elseif $personality == "kind">>You pout. "How is that a bad thing?"

"See," she says, entirely unbothered, "You're proving my point."

You pout harder. Then give up and chuckle.<<else>>"Even if I what?" you ask.

She waves a hand. "You know. Whatever it is you are this week."

"I have range you know." 

"See," she says entirely expressionless, "you're proving my point."<</if>>

"Rude."  You say as you lightly kick her under the table which makes her snort "But I love you too."

"Cheers to that." She lifts her cup, smiling, and knocks it gently against yours.

You hear commotion outside, but you’re chatting with your friend and you find in that moment that you don't particularly care. 

You think, not for the first time, how lucky you were. That of everywhere you could have landed, the Moon put you here, with her.
But then the noise picks up again, louder this time as the source is getting closer.

[[Until it becomes overwhelming.|tavernfinal]]




:: tavern10lour {"position":"6275,500","size":"100,100"}
“What do you mean? You’re not alone. I’m here”

The words land before you can think about them. Lou goes still for half a second, then flushes bright red all the way to the tips of her ears. 

"I didn't mean— that's not—" you start, and now the heat is rushing to //your// face too. 

"It's fine." She laughs softly and waves a hand, eyes focusing on the far wall, avoiding your gaze "I know what you meant." 

Silence settles between you, warm and excruciating in equal measure. You would groan if you weren't already mortified. 

//Moon above, this is pathetic.//

She drags a finger absently over the rim of her cup. Then, quietly: "I'm here for you too. You know that, right?" 

You say nothing because what else is there to say? You’re lying to her. And you have been everyday since you met her. So instead you raise your drink. 

“Cheers” 

She smiles before lifting her cup and knocking it gently against yours. 

"Cheers."

You hear commotion outside, but Lou is smiling at you like you're sharing a secret, and you find in that moment that you don't particularly care. 

You think, not for the first time, how lucky you were. That of everywhere you could have landed, the moon put you here, with her.
But then the noise picks up again, louder this time as the source is getting closer, and it seems to break the spell between the two of you.

  [[Until it becomes overwhelming.|tavernfinal]]
  


:: tavern2angry {"position":"5275,350","size":"100,100"}
You breathe out through your nose, the vulnerability twists into something uglier.

“What do you think?” You snap.

You see Lou's face fall a little, and you already regret your words. You know she can sense you're not feeling well, asking this sort of question feels useless and makes you angry, short tempered.
That's the worst part you think, you always know, even as it's happening. It's not about trust. As far as trust goes, Lou is the only person alive who has earned it, fully, without question. It's not even about the lie, though the lie sits in your chest like a stone.

You just don't want to talk about it. 

She's asking out of concern. You know that. Of course you know that. 
The pit at the bottom of your stomach deepens. You feel shame, and then feel angry for feeling shame, a neat little spiral you've gotten good at lately. //Shouldn't she know by now?// And then the darker turn, the one that comes right after: // why are you always like this? Why do you always bite the hand that feeds you.//

//Since when did you become so difficult?//

You know when. 

Lou stays quiet with that particular patience of hers.  She doesn't push. You can feel the curiosity simmering off her, but that's Lou, she'll wait you out, give you the rope and let you decide whether to climb it or hang yourself with it. Some days, you wish you could do the latter. 
It's only been a few years, but sometimes it feels like she knows you better than you know yourself.
Well. Except for the //I turn into a wolf once a month// part.

[[Next.|tavern3]]


:: tavern2funny {"position":"5150,300","size":"100,100"}
“What ? Not even a //Hello, how are you doing my friend, what a beautiful day we're having. lovely to see you as always//… I’m hurt”

She crosses her arms, leaning back on her feet.

“Oh sorry, Hello $mc, what a beautiful day we're having, You look terrible, spill it. Better?”

“That's awful customer service, Ser”

"Only for you my friend." 

“And here I thought I was your favorite customer”

She gives you a look of absolute pity  "You steal food off my plates and run a tab you never close. Charles tips." She shakes her head slowly. "It's not even close."  She replies, eyes full of mirth.

You make a fake offended gasp before you both chuckle.

It's always been like that with Lou, like a mirror the banter and the teasing flow easily between the two of you ever since the first day. Perhaps that's why you were so keen on being close friends with her. Not only do you like her company but she also has a way to soothe the wolf within you. The pillar of solitude that never seems to leave your chest always feels a little less heavy when you're with her.

She doesn't push. You can feel the curiosity simmering off her, but that's Lou, she'll wait you out, give you the rope and let you decide whether to climb it or hang yourself with it. Some days, you wish you could do the latter. 
It's only been a few years, but sometimes it feels like she knows you better than you know yourself.
Well. Except for the //I turn into a wolf once a month// part.

[[Next.|tavern3]]


:: tavern2kind {"position":"5275,500","size":"100,100"}
"Just slept badly is all. thanks for asking."

Lou hums, you get the sense she doesn't believe you but she isn't pushing yet. She glances toward the window. 

"Full moon last night. Probably that." 

You freeze.
She knows. //She knows.//

The thought hits like cold water, and for a moment you can't breathe. You can feel the chill crawling up from the back of your neck to the bottom of your spine, your hands already sweating, motionless on the table.

"What did you say?" you manage to croak.

She turns her attention back on you, brows high. "The moon? It was full last night. I woke up before dawn and thought it was already day, it was so bright I nearly knocked a candle over getting out of bed, actually, because I was so convinced the sun was up." She waves a hand. "Anyway. I've heard midwives say it messes with your sleep, the full moon. Something to do with the light, or the tide, or the spirits or … I don't know, the body just knows somehow." She tilts her head. "Don't know if there's truth to it or if it's just..." 

She trails off. Her lips press together.

The tension bleeds out of you so fast you have to work not to slump forward.

//She doesn't know.//

"Or just?" It's a dangerous game you’re playing and yet you prompt her anyway, because you’re a fool and you need to hear it. 

She leans in slightly, dropping her voice. "Witches' talk," she says, barely above a whisper. "You know how people are. Someone's cow dies, someone's baby won't sleep, someone's bread doesn't rise. witches" She rolls her eyes, then catches herself and glances around the room. 

You do the same for entirely different reasons as you feel your stomach clenches. 
She shouldn't talk like this. Not here and not so freely, not where anyone could be listening. Not when a priest is literally a few tables away. The witch hunts are long over, yes. Everyone says so. But you know the Church hasn't stopped, hasn't ever stopped, will never stop, hunting anything that doesn't fit its idea of normal.

Everything like //you//. 

When you don’t respond, she stays quiet for a while. She doesn't push. You can feel the curiosity simmering off her, but that's Lou, she'll wait you out, give you the rope and let you decide whether to climb it or hang yourself with it. Some days, you wish you could do the latter. 

It's only been a few years, but sometimes it feels like she knows you better than you know yourself.
Well. Except for the //I turn into a wolf once a month// part.

[[Next.|tavern3]] <<set $honest +=1>>


:: tavern2quiet {"position":"5150,550","size":"100,100"}
You grumble, not particularly feeling like putting words to it, and Lou catches on without missing a beat. She always does.

It's been like that since the beginning. She talks, you listen. Two sides of the same coin, she fills the silence and you inhabit it. Somehow it works, has always worked, in a way you didn't expect and didn't quite know how to receive at first. 

You're not easy company. You know that. 

You run quiet where she runs loud, you pull inward where she spills outward, and yet somehow the shape of her fits neatly against the shape of you, like two people cut from the same cloth by different hands.

Maybe that's part of why you took to her so easily. Why you wanted her close.

But it's more than just compatibility, more than liking her company, though you do. It's something harder to name. Lou has a way of settling something in you that doesn't settle easily, something old and restless that lives just beneath the surface and doesn't care much for people as a rule. 

She reminds you of your grandmother, sometimes. 

Not in the way she looks or the things she says, but in the quality of her presence. The way she makes a room feel smaller in the good sense. Safe. Contained. Your grandmother had that too, and you hadn't realised how much you'd been missing it until Lou sat across from you one idle afternoon, rambling about something inconsequential, and you noticed distantly that your grief had gone quiet. 

That the solitude you carry, the pillar of it, permanent and load-bearing, felt for once a little less like something you had to hold up on your own.

It still comes back. It always comes back. But it's lighter here. With her.

She doesn't push. You can feel the curiosity simmering off her, but that's Lou, she'll wait you out, give you the rope and let you decide whether to climb it or hang yourself with it. Some days, you wish you could do the latter. 

It's only been a few years, but sometimes it feels like she knows you better than you know yourself.
Well. Except for the //I turn into a wolf once a month// part.

[[Next.|tavern3]]


:: tavern3 {"position":"5400,425","size":"100,100"}
<<cycle "$tellher" autoselect>>
	<<option "You want to tell her but you can't">>
	<<option "You're too scared to even think about this conversation.">>
<</cycle>> 
You love her, she is your friend, the only person you have left now, and there are moments when you want nothing more than to tell her. All of it. To finally be known, wholly, by someone who matters to you.

But your grandmother's warning has never left you. //Be careful who you tell. Be careful what you are to people. //  

Werewolves are creatures of the devil in the eyes of the world, to be killed at best and tortured at worst. And the thought of Lou looking at you differently. Of seeing the fear replace the warmth in her eyes. Of losing her the way you've lost everyone else. 

You don't think you could survive that. Not after losing your grandmother. Not when Lou is the only person alive who loves you. 

So you stay in the limbo you've made for yourself. Craving kinship and wanting desperately to be seen, known and accepted. And yet, keeping the door shut. Because being half-known feels safer than being wholly rejected.

You're not sure it is, though. Safer.

You're not sure of much anymore.

[[Next.|tavern4]]


:: tavern4 {"position":"5525,425","size":"100,100"}
<<if $tellher == "You want to tell her but you can't">><<set $honest += 5>> <</if>>
“You wanna know about somethin' I've heard?”

You see the mirth in her eyes, as a conspiratory smile splits her face as she leans towards you and speaks softer so no one can spy on your conversation. If your hearing wasn't as sharp, you probably wouldn't be able to pick up what she's even saying.

“You know of Lison, from Saint-Bonnet ? The one who exclusively wears those absolutely dreadful green dresses” she pauses as if the fashion crime alone requires a moment of silence. “Rumor has it she's been spending an awful lot of time with Tristan, you know the traveling merchant.”

“Wasn't she promised to the tanner?” 

Now what was his name? //Sylvio ?//

“She was! But apparently there's been a fight between Sylvain and Tristan. I've heard that Tristan even called the Bayle to the fight.”

“The //Bayle//? Over a lovers' quarrel ?” You lean on your forearms. “Why would anyone drag the lord's own man into this? What's he going to do, fine Sylvain over a bloodied nose ?” 

"I know." She sits back, deeply satisfied. "Look, you've seen Tristan. Scrawny as a scarecrow. He knew he couldn't take Sylvain in a fair fight so he made sure it wouldn't be one." She shakes her head. "A bit cowardly, if you ask me. I genuinely don't know what Lison sees in him. Probably the coin, but that feels rude to say… Although she is unsufferable, so maybe she deserves it." 

“So what did Sylvain do then ?”

“Well apparently he tried to woo her back” She pauses for effect. “With a poem. And flowers.”

You stare at her.

"I know!" she says again with a laugh.

  [[“Poor Sod”|tavern5]]
  [[You Nod without saying a word.|tavern5][$quiet += 1]]


:: tavern5 {"position":"5650,425","size":"100,100"}
You shake your head slowly, picking at a wine stain on the table. 

You hear two strangers enter the Inn, and you watch as Lou looks behind her back before rising from her seat. Duty calls.

“What do you want to drink? Same as usual?”

Alcohol makes you queasy. It's a werewolf thing that you know for sure, cause grandma used to tell you wild tales of your mom drinking alcohol and being terribly sick afterwards. The only other food that makes werewolf sick is a rare delicacy you've never seen in France so far; chocolate.

[[You drink alcohol, like your mother, you're trying to build a resistance to it.|tavern6][$drink to "wine"; $tempdrink to "wine"]]
[[You don't drink alcohol, so you usually have an infusion.|tavern6][$drink to "tea"; $tempdrink to "tea"]]
[[You usually drink alcohol, but you'll have an infusion for once.|tavern6][$drink to "wine"; $tempdrink to "tea"]]
[[You usually drink herbal tea, but after the night you had you'll have some alcohol.|tavern6][$drink to "tea"; $tempdrink to "wine"]]


:: tavern6 {"position":"5775,425","size":"100,100"}
“Got it” She winks before heading and welcoming the travelers.

You don't mind people watching while Lou tends to the Inn. You do realize now it's been a while since you've last seen the bard, you note as other regulars enter the Inn to drink and play dice.
You try to listen to what people are saying but after the rumors Lou shared, it really pales in comparison. So instead you chose to look at Lou while she works.

The door hinge squeaks.

You look up out of habit, old instinct integrated into you, always know who's coming in,  and feel your shoulders tighten slightly when you see who it is.

Father Benoît.

He's a small, tranquil man, somewhere around sixty, with thin white hair cropped close around a tonsure that time has done most of the work on anyway. He's not from the village, he’s the parish priest of the nearby town of Saint-Bonnet-de-Montauroux —  called Saint-Bonnet by the locals —  Tierce-Lieux depends on since it’s too small to have a priest of its own. He stays at the inn when he’s here. He makes the trip every few weeks or so to deliver his sermons at the chapel, and generally ensures, with quiet and unassuming thoroughness, that everything here runs according to the Church's liking.
The local nobles find this arrangement a source of constant irritation. The village may fall within their domain, but Father Benoît answers to the bishop of Mende, not to them. The souls of every villager fall under his care long before they fall under any lord's concern. Father Benoît, for his part, seems unbothered by their feelings on the matter.

You don't dislike the man. That's the honest truth of it. He's never been anything but decent to you.
Still. Men of the cloth make you nervous. They always have.

//For obvious reasons.//

There's a boy with him, blond curly hair hiding light blue eyes. He must be fifteen winters or so, and he’s hovering a step behind with the look of someone still learning where to put themselves. You're not well-versed in how the Church organises its own, but you guess he’s an apprentice of sorts.

Lou greets them both with the easy warmth she has for everyone, and within moments she's chatting away like she's known them for years. Even the boy seems more at ease with her. You watch her from across the room, you see the small dimple made by her smile, her green-blue eyes almost sparkling when she laughs at something the priest says, all smiles and no effort. 
So very different from you.

You get newcomers often enough, the village sitting on the main road as it does. Lou never seems to mind. 

<<if setup.gender.pronouns().noun == "man">><span style="color:gray;">You've been in love with her for a while now.</span><<else>> <<link "You've been in love with her for a while now">> <<set $lou_r += 3>> <<goto "tavern7">> <</link>><</if>>
<<link "You love her like a friend, a sister.">>
  <<goto "tavern7">>
<</link>>


:: tavern7 {"position":"5900,425","size":"100,100"}
You don't know how you could have survived without her. When your grandma died, you were all alone, and there's no worse fate for a werewolf, to be utterly alone. Werewolves are, at their very core, creatures built for a pack; a tight-knit group of people who know you, who see you, who //hold// you. Friends, lovers, family, it doesn't matter what shape it takes. What matters is that it's there.

Without it…

Well, there is a reason solitary werewolves are cautionary tales. The emptiness becomes too much to bear, rotting into something unrecognisable. Anger, bitterness, pride; a slow withdrawal from everything soft and human until there's not much left worth saving. A wounded animal that's forgotten it was ever anything else. 

	That's probably why you value your friendship with Lou so much. You were definitely not a fun person to be around when she met you, not by a long stretch. You lost your grandma, your only tether, and then you moved to a small village in the middle of Gévaudan. 
    
    Nowhere in other words. 
    
    You were withdrawn, sullen, and even misanthropic at times. While everyone treated you with kindness in the village, Lou was the only one who really stuck around. Who bothered to look after the broken pieces that you were, no matter how much it cut her in the process. 

When the grief started to recede, you feared she would be gone. After all, some people love to fix others, love the broken version, and lose interest once it starts to heal.  But no, Lou stayed. You had a renewed appreciation for her steady presence through it all.

<<if $lou_r == 3>>You're not sure when the feeling changed from friends to something more on your part, but you do know you've felt like this for a while. But still you get this fluttering feeling in your stomach whenever she smiles at you, this urge to keep her close and happy and safe. You wish you could help her like she helped you. But she seems very in control of her life compared to you.
You almost kissed her once. And you could swear she was leaning in too, but honestly you could have imagined that, you must have. 

You know Lou. 

If she likes someone she goes for it. She is not one to dance around matters of the heart.

You were both outside, stargazing in front of your house. You talked about everything and nothing. The moonlight was softly lighting up her face, making her freckles stand out even more. Her cheeks, nose and lips were slightly more pink than usual, it was a cold night.

Her sea-green eyes seemed to almost glow in the moonlight. She seemed so at ease, calmer than when she is working. She turned to look at you and you remember every detail of her face that you wanted to carve directly into your memory. Her lips slightly parted and you could not take your gaze off lips.

The moment stretched longer than what is acceptable between friends, and then an owl screamed and broke the spell. You definitely felt your cheeks heat up and, while your color vision at night is not great, you could swear she was blushing. But then again, maybe that's wishful thinking on your part.<br><br><</if>>You see Lou coming back with your drink, a glass of $tempdrink, before she settles back in her chair.

  [[Next.|tavern8]]


:: tavern8 {"position":"6025,425","size":"100,100"}
Things have quieted down. Most people have been served and settled into their own conversations, the low hum of voices filling the room. Lou comes back to your table with two drinks and drops back into her chair.

Usually there'd be more people at this hour, especially this time of year. The rain probably accounts for some of it. But if you're being honest, the likelier reason is sitting two tables over in his travelling robes: you've noticed that Father Benoît has a particular effect on the tavern's headcount. People who would otherwise be on their third drink by now suddenly remember they have somewhere else to be, or simply never show up at all, eager to be seen as the kind of person who doesn't frequent such places.

Whatever that means, you think, taking a sip of your drink.

"At least she has someone." Lou says after a while, cutting through your thoughts. "Or options, anyway." 

“What?”

“Lison” She's not looking at you, her gaze has drifted to the fire crackling in the corner, like she's turning something over in her mind. 

“Where are you going with this?” You frown. 

She sighs, putting both her palms on the table. "Look. I just-" 

She stops. You wait. 

It's not often that Lou is struggling to find her words. She usually has too many of them. But here she looks almost small. The firelight catches the side of her face and you find yourself wondering, not for the first time, if she's lonelier than she lets on.

[[”What's wrong?”|tavern9][$kind +=1]]
[[”What?”|tavern9][$angry +=1]]
[[Look at her with a questioning look.|tavern9][$quiet +=1]]
[[”Penny for your thoughts?”|tavern9][$funny +=1]]


:: tavern9 {"position":"6150,425","size":"100,100"}
"You'll say I'm being dramatic."

"You are."

She laughs, and the tension goes out of her shoulders. "Fine, fine -" A pause. She turns her cup in her hands. "It's just... it's hard sometimes, living out here. We're so far from anywhere." She glances at you sideways. "Do you have any idea how difficult it is to find a woman who likes someone like me?"
