:: warmbath {"position":"1700,525","size":"100,100"}
<<set $stress += 3>><<set $warmbath to "true">>
The day after a transformation is, at least, easier on the body than the days before. The aches are gone. The Moon is generous that way, whatever the curse breaks she puts back together by morning. Joints and muscles that screamed yesterday are silent and steady now.

You should be grateful for that. Probably.

It doesn't make the monthly ritual of it any less exhausting. The healing is real, but so is everything that preceded it. The bone-deep pain of the days before, the transformation itself, and then the morning after, when you come back to yourself piece by piece and have to figure out what you've done.

The body recovers. The rest takes longer.

The warm water will help. It always does. And in the meantime, the strategy, as always, is to be methodical. Keep your hands busy. Keep moving.

You set the pot over the fire first, filling it from the bucket you'd thought to bring in the night before, and while it heats you turn to the rest of the house. The clothes you'd shed in a hurry the night before get folded or set aside. You take up the broom and work the dried mud out from the floor in long steady strokes. It had followed you in with the morning, caked into the grain of the wood. Sweeping helps. It keeps your mind from circling back

By the time the water is ready, the house looks like itself again. 

You pour the pot into the basin.

[[Now. You.|bath1]]


:: wood1 {"position":"950,450","size":"100,100"}
<span class="typed-text"><<typed60>>\''June 1764, County of Gévaudan
Present Day''<</typed60>></span>
//Shit.//

That's your first thought as you come back on to yourself. The ground is cold, it’s dawn and you’re bloody, partially naked in the middle of the forest. And while you don’t hurt anymore you still feel the ache of the transformation in your muscles and joints, like a phantom pain. You feel the iron taste on your tongue. There's a light ringing in your ears. Your vision is still sharp. Your senses are still heightened, as they often are around the full moon. 

Now here's the thing though; this isn't the first time.
For a few months now you've been having episodes. Waking up in the forest, with remnants of clothes, and sometimes none. The carcass of the latest animal you killed nearby. Little memory of what happened between dusk and dawn. Fragments, at best. A smell. A taste. A sound. The feeling of running.

The rest is dark.

You feel:
[[Calm|WoodCalm]]
[[Completely Panicked|WoodPanic]]
[[Stressed but you will remain calm|WoodRepressed]]


:: wood2 {"position":"1200,450","size":"100,100"}
At the very least you know more or less where you are, the stash tree shouldn't be too far.

You try to keep an eye out to see if you can find the body of whatever you killed but beside the blood on yourself you don't smell any blood around the area. Maybe you ate and then kept running.
You genuinely have no idea how wolves work. How //you// work. You should have gone with your grandmother on her hunts when you had the chance. 

You didn't. And now here you are trying to solve the mystery alone. Alone, and half naked in the forest.

	After walking for a few minutes you find the stash tree, the one that you always leave a few clothes in, for situations just like these. 

The tree is an old beech tree which, sadly, seemed to have died from illness a few years prior, but is still standing tall. A fox found it before you did. The damned creature kept stealing your clothes, and when you tracked it down it was hiding in the hollow. Now your first thought was to leave it alone but the fox actually peed on your clothes too. You'd meant to leave it alone. You were having a bad night. One thing led to another and you fought the damn fox. It obviously lost but not before biting your wrist and leaving a nasty scar. It does come back from time to time, but you're fairly certain it's purely out of spite, as sometimes you still find your clothes reeking of piss.

	It is quite annoying how many clothes you've torn in the past few months.
True you became better at stitching clothes, at least the ones salvageable, but it's still nothing great. In the past few weeks you bought so many clothes it's beginning to cost a small fortune. So you had to buy less expensive clothes, and sometimes even clothes that didn’t fit you at all. Your hand reaches out into the core of the hollow tree, hoping, because it happened once, that those awful tiny insects didn’t decide on a whim to feast on your clothes.

You take out a grayish shirt and some earth toned pants. Nothing fancy, and nothing really comfortable. And while they both have holes here and there, they seem mostly okay as you inspect them. You sniff them for good measure. No fox piss. That’s good. 

	You put them on.

//What is your height wolfkin?//
[[Very Small (Below 1m55)|woodclothes][$height to "very small"]]
[[Small (1m55 -1m60)|woodclothes][$height to "small"]]
[[Average (1m60-1m70)|woodclothes][$height to "average"]]
